title: For Sale:  Sub MOA Ruger AR-556 with same upper and lower casting as Rock River Arms
postcontent: Ruger AR-556 with over 100 rounds and two magazines.Tactical-Life.com Gun Review: FEB 2, 2015 BY DAVE BAHDEThe Battle-Ready Ruger AR-556Note: The upper and lower receiver have the same casting as Rock River Arms (see red arrows in photo).The rifle starts with forged 7075-T6 aluminum upper and lower receivers that have been Type III hardcoat anodized for durability. The upper receiver features a cold-hammer-forged, chrome-moly, medium-contour steel barrel. Measuring 16.1 inches long, the barrel has a 1-in-8-inch twist and a 5.56mm NATO chamber with M4 feed ramps. It also has 1/2×28 threading for adding suppressors and comes with a standard flash suppressor.The upper also features a chrome-plated bolt carrier with a properly staked gas key. A matte black oxide finish on the exterior of the bolt carrier provides corrosion resistance. Built from 9310 steel, the bolt has been shot-peened and magnetic-particle (MP) inspected. The upper includes an ejection port cover, a forward assist and a brass deflector. The front sight is milled with a serrated rear ramp to cut down on glare. This sight sits at the standard A2 height, so it works with any rear sight, and a quick-detach (QD) sling flush cup is included on the bottom—a really nice touch. Ruger also includes a windage-adjustable, flip-up Rapid Deploy rear sight. The A2-style forend, made from heat-resistant, glass-filled nylon, is attached to the upper using a modified delta ring. Simply unscrew the ring and any M4-compatible handguard can be added—no tools are necessary.The mil-spec, six-position buffer tube holds an M4-style collapsible buttstock. Ruger has also outfitted the lower receiver with an ergonomic pistol grip and an enlarged trigger guard. The single-stage trigger is crisp and predictable, with minimal crunch and creep and no over travel. It should meet any duty requirements. The quality of my test rifle was apparent immediately after pulling it out of the box. There is nothing about this rifle that screams compromise. In fact, it is as well built as many rifles that cost twice as much.

title: For Sale:  DWM Model 1914 Artillery Luger & Holster, Blue 7 7/8” MATCHING SA Semi-Automatic Pistol, MFD 1917 C&R 9mm Parabellum
postcontent: DWM Model: 1914 Artillery Luger Serial Number: 1507d Year of Manufacture: 1917 Caliber: 9mm Parabellum Action Type: Single Action Semi-Auto with Removable Magazine Markings: The top of the rear sight base, the rear face of the sight, the left rear of the elevator, the right side of the slider, sear bar, sear bar safety, the top of the front toggle and the back of the rear toggle, the locking bolt, the left side of the trigger and the left sideplate are marked “07”. The extractor is unmarked. The left side of the frame just behind the trigger is marked “H and the inside of the sideplate is marked “I”. The top of the front toggle is also marked with “DWM” in script. The chamber is marked “1917” at the top and “1507” on the left side. The underside of the round part of the barrel is marked “1507 / d / 8,83” and the front end of the frame just behind it is marked “1507 / d”. The well at the front of the frame is marked with an “N” in a circle and “P”. The top right side of the hold-open latch is marked “07”. The bottom of the barrel at the chamber is marked on the left side with “Q”, on the bottom of the lug with “N” and on the right side with “W”. The left underside of the rear toggle link is also marked “N”. The right side of the chamber is marked with three crowned proofs which appear to be “T, S and S”, and an Eagle. These proofs are as shown on line 10 page 234 of ”Luger Variations” by H.E. Jones, and are correct for a 1914 DWM military pistol. The 5th mark, a sideways Eagle, is marked on the right side of the barrel just in front of the frame, and there is another Eagle on the left side of the breechblock. The left side of the frame under the safety is marked “Gesichert”. The underside of the left grip panel is marked “0”, “07” and “H”. The underside of the right grip is marked “07”, “H” and “K”. Barrel Length: 7 7/8” Sights / Optics: This pistol is mounted with a blade front sight that is dovetailed into a base on the front barrel band and has a serrated and ramped rear face. The front sight has a windage adjustment via a screw on its right side with two holes for a spanner wrench. The tangent artillery rear sight is flat topped with a “V” notch and the elevator has graduated markings from 1-8. The elevation can be fine-tuned via a spanner wrench adjustment. The sights are known as the “Fine Tuning” Artillery Sights. Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are checkered walnut. The left grip shows oil staining along its front and rear edges, while the right grip is lightly spotted with oil staining. The checkering shows light wear tending to moderate wear at the edges. There are a few tiny mars in the right grip and left grip, with a slightly larger mar in the center of the left grip. The left grip is slightly loose on the frame. The grips rate in about Fine overall condition. Type of Finish: The pistol is blued. The trigger, safety, locking bolt, ejector and the right side of the magazine release are straw colored. The sear bar safety is “In The White” and the sear bar spring has a fire blue finish. Finish Originality: The finish is original. Shipping is free
